Don’t fear learning Data Visualization in R with ggplot

geze

10/16/2019

Yet another great free-software tool.

I recommend “Data Visualization: A Practical Introduction” by K. Healy because it is listed by the Society of Actuaries SOA for their PA-exam.This is a file written in Rstudio.

First install the library tidyverse with install.packages("tidyverse") and load it with library(tidyverse). This includes the library ggplot2, which is the main object of this tutorial. I will be using the csv file obtained here.

The first plot

Our first plot will begin by loading the library tidyverse.

library(tidyverse)

Then we will load our csv file with the function read_csv. This will print all the attributes or columns together with their types:

housing <- read_csv("~/ml/data/housing.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(

##   ocean_proximity = col_character()
## )

Finally, we will make our first own plot using the attributes longitude and lattitude. Notice that first we call the function ggplot, which loads the data. It also contains the aesthetic function telling R which is our X variable, which is our Y variable, and another variable color to be explained later. Then we use the function geom_point() to tell R actually to make a scatterplot.

ggplot(data = housing, mapping = aes(x = longitude, y = latitude, color = ocean_proximity)) + geom_point()

Remark: The option color in aes does not choose what color will be used, but it tells R to use different colors for the different classes in the attribute ocean_proximity.

Just to make sure that we understand ocean_proximity, we do a histogram of it. Here one may opt using the library plpr:

ggplot(data = housing, aes(ocean_proximity)) + geom_bar(fill =  "#800080" )+ labs(tittle = "Frequency of Ocean Proximity Values")

Overview of the syntax

The main elements of a plot are:

  1. ggplot(data, aes(X,Y,color,fill) wheredata is usually the table variable; X and Y are some attributes in our table; color and fill tell R to color based on a classifying attribute, the former is for dots, and the later for areas.

  2. geom_<type> is to decide the type or types of graph(s) that we will use.

  • geom_point(alpha = 0.d, color, shape, size, line_type) is for scatterplots.
  • geom_bar(color, shape, size, line_type) is for bars.
  • geom_boxplot(color, shape, size, line_type) is for boxplots.
  • geom_smooth(color, se = boolean, size, method, formula, mapping) is for optimization models. Some methods are lm for linear models, gam for generalized additive models, loess.
  1. cord_cartesian(xlim = c(a,b), ylim= c(c,d)) to delimit the region of the cartesian plane to observe.
  2. scale_x_log10, scale_x_reverse, scale_x_sqr or their respective ones for y to adjust the scales.
  3. labs(x, y, tittle, subtittle) to add labels to the plot.
  4. ggsave(filename, plot_variable_name)

Finally, recall that you add all these elements, and write + at the end of the line, so R understands that there is more code coming.

A much better graph.

ggplot(data = housing, mapping = aes(x = longitude, y = latitude, color = ocean_proximity)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.1) + geom_smooth(method = 'lm') + labs(x = "longitude", y = "latitude", tittle = "location of the houses", subtittle = "sorted by proximity to the ocean") + facet_wrap(~ocean_proximity)

Notice the last option facet_wrap(~ocean_proximity) allows us to do one graph per class in the attribute ocean_proximity.

For more details, see the documentation of ggplot. Quoting Wikipedia, ggplot is a data visualization package for R created by Hadley Wickham in 2005, ggplot2 is an implementation of Leland Wilkinson’s Grammar of Graphics.
